<text top="105" left="55" width="499" height="15" font="font9" id="p1_t7" reading_order_no="4" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">Reconstructing protein structure from solvent exposure using tabu<a href="http://www.biomedcentral.com/info/about/charter/"><b>Open Access</b></a></text>
<text top="123" left="55" width="49" height="15" font="font9" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="5" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">search</text>
<text top="140" left="55" width="405" height="14" font="font10" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="6" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">Martin Paluszewski* 1 , Thomas Hamelryck 2 and Pawel Winter 1<b>Reconstructing protein structure from solvent exposure using tabu </b></text>
<text top="175" left="55" width="498" height="9" font="font12" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="7" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Address: 1 Department of Computer Science, University of Copenhagen, Universitetsparken 1, 2100 Copenhagen, Denmark and 2 Bioinformatics<b>search</b></text>
<text top="185" left="55" width="452" height="8" font="font12" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="8" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Center, Institute of Molecular Biology, University of Copenhagen, Universitetsparken 15 building 10, 2100 Copenhagen, Denmark</text>
<text top="200" left="55" width="417" height="8" font="font12" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="9" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">Email: Martin Paluszewski* - palu@diku.dk; Thomas Hamelryck - thamelry@binf.ku.dk; Pawel Winter - pawel@diku.dk</text>
<text top="211" left="55" width="92" height="8" font="font12" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="10" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">* Corresponding author</text>
<text top="359" left="112" width="44" height="10" font="font14" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="20" segment_no="16" tag_type="title">Abstract</text>
<text top="374" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="21" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">Background: A new, promising solvent exposure measure, called half-sphere-exposure (HSE), has</text>
<text top="386" left="112" width="385" height="11" font="font16" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="22" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">recently been proposed. Here, we study the reconstruction of a protein's C Î± trace solely from</text>
<text top="398" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="23" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">structure-derived HSE information. This problem is of relevance for de novo structure prediction</text>
<text top="409" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="24" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">using predicted HSE measure. For comparison, we also consider the well-established contact</text>
<text top="421" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="25" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">number (CN) measure. We define energy functions based on the HSE- or CN-vectors and</text>
<text top="433" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="26" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">minimize them using two conformational search heuristics: Monte Carlo simulation (MCS) and tabu</text>
<text top="445" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font17" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="27" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">search (TS). While MCS has been the dominant conformational search heuristic in literature, TS has</text>
<text top="456" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">been applied only a few times. To discretize the conformational space, we use lattice models with</text>
<text top="468" left="112" width="77" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">various complexity.</text>
<text top="485" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">Results: The proposed TS heuristic with a novel tabu definition generally performs better than<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;dopt=Abstract&amp;list_uids=17069644">  </a></text>
<text top="497" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">MCS for this problem. Our experiments show that, at least for small proteins (up to 35 amino<b>Abstract</b></text>
<text top="508" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">acids), it is possible to reconstruct the protein backbone solely from the HSE or CN information.<b>Background: </b></text>
<text top="520" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">In general, the HSE measure leads to better models than the CN measure, as judged by the RMSD</text>
<text top="532" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t28" reading_order_no="34" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">and the angle correlation with the native structure. The angle correlation, a measure of structural<i>half-sphere-exposure </i></text>
<text top="544" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t29" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">similarity, evaluates whether equivalent residues in two structures have the same general</text>
<text top="555" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">orientation. Our results indicate that the HSE measure is potentially very useful to represent</text>
<text top="567" left="112" width="283" height="9" font="font16" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">solvent exposure in protein structure prediction, design and simulation.<i>C</i></text>
<text top="617" left="55" width="60" height="10" font="font14" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="20" tag_type="title">Background</text>
<text top="628" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">The extent to which an amino acid in a protein is accessi-</text>
<text top="640" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">ble to the surrounding solvent is highly dependent on the</text>
<text top="652" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">type of amino acid. In general, hydrophilic amino acids<i>de novo </i></text>
<text top="663" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">tend to be near the solvent accessible surface, while hydro-</text>
<text top="675" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t37" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">phobic amino acids tend to be buried in the core of the</text>
<text top="687" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">protein. To measure this effect, several solvent exposure</text>
<text top="698" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">measures have been proposed [1-7], and one of these is</text>
<text top="710" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">the contact number measure (CN) [7]. The CN of a residue<i>Monte Carlo simulation </i></text>
<text top="722" left="55" width="241" height="12" font="font20" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">is the number of C Î± atoms in a sphere centered at the C Î±</text>
<text top="616" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="19" tag_type="text">atom of the residue in question (Figure 1). The CN of all<i>tabu</i></text>
<text top="628" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="19" tag_type="text">residues of a protein is called the CN vector . The CN vector<i>search </i></text>
<text top="640" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="19" tag_type="text">is well conserved and can be predicted with high accuracy</text>
<text top="652" left="313" width="15" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="51" segment_no="19" tag_type="text">[8].</text>
<text top="675" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="52" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">Recently, a new promising solvent exposure measure,</text>
<text top="687" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="53" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">called half-sphere-exposure (HSE), has been proposed [9].<b>Results: </b></text>
<text top="698" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">While the CN measure uses a single sphere centered at the</text>
<text top="710" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font21" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="55" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">C Î± atom, the HSE measure considers two hemispheres.</text>
<text top="722" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font20" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="56" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">Two values, an up and a down value, are associated with</text>
<text top="254" left="55" width="91" height="7" font="font23" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="11" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">Published: 27 October 2006</text>
